rt, Meurthe-et-Moselle, Lorraine, Frankrijk","Whitby, Yorkshire, England":"Whitby, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"abt 1374–25 Oct 1415":"about 1374–25 October 1415","1374–1415":"1374–1415","1378–Female":"1378–Deceased","1400–1445":"1400–1445","1410–1475":"1410–1475","1312–1380":"1312–1380","1316–Female":"1316–Deceased","1374":"1374","abt 1374":"about 1374","1380":"1380","abt 1410":"about 1410","1316":"1316","1415":"1415","1445":"1445","1400":"1400","1312":"1312","1378":"1378","1410":"1410","1475":"1475","25 Oct 1415":"25 October 1415","Whitstone, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom":"Whitstone, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","North Petherwin, Cornwall, England":"North Petherwin, Cornwall, England","Battle of Agincourt, Lorraine,  France":"Agincourt, Meurthe-et-Moselle, Lorraine, France","Whitby, Yorkshire, England":"Whitby, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Goode","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Midlands): variant of   Good  . This name has been used in Ireland since the 16th century.","Possibly an Americanized form of Dutch   Goede  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Good","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>gode</i> ‘good’ (Old English <i>gōd</i>).","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Gode</i>, representing either Old English <i>Goda</i> (male) or <i>Gode</i> (female), in part a byname and in part a short form of various compound names with the first element <i>gōd</i>, or perhaps a pet form of Old French names in <i>God-</i> such as   Godfrey  .","Americanized form (translation into English) of German   Gut   and   Guth  , or Dutch <b>Goed</b> and   Goede  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Goode was born about 1374, in Whitstone, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom, his father, William Alton Goode, was 63 and his mother, Bettey Elaine Cobb, was 60. He had at least 2 sons with Penelope. He died on 25 October 1415, in Agincourt, Meurthe-et-Moselle, Lorraine, France, at the age of 42."},"et":{"abt 1374–25 Oct 1415":"umbes 1374–25. oktoober 1415","1374–1415":"1374–1415","1378–Female":"1378–Surnud","1400–1445":"1400–1445","1410–1475":"1410–1475","1312–1380":"1312–1380","1316–Female":"1316–Surnud","1374":"1374","abt 1374":"umbes 1374","1380":"1380","abt 1410":"umbes 1410","1316":"1316","1415":"1415","1445":"1445","1400":"1400","1312":"1312","1378":"1378","1410":"1410","1475":"1475","25 Oct 1415":"25. oktoober 1415","Whitstone, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom":"Whitstone, Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","North Petherwin, Cornwall, England":"North Petherwin, Cornwall, England","Battle of Agincourt, Lorraine,  France":"Agincourt, Meurthe-et-Moselle, Lorraine, Prantsusmaa","Whitby, Yorkshire, England":"Whitby, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"abt 1374–25 Oct 1415":"noin 1374–25. lokakuuta 1415","1374–1415":"1374–1415","1378–Female":"1378–Kuollut","1400–1445":"1400–1445","1410–1475":"1410–1475","1312–1380":"1312–1380","1316–Female":"1316–Kuollut","1374":"1374","abt 1374":"noin 1374","1380":"1380","abt 1410":"noin 1410","1316":"1316","1415":"1415","1445":"1445","1400":"1400","1312":"1312","1378":"1378","1410